Part I - (Dataset Exploration Title)¶

By Metasebiya Akililu Bizuneh¶

Introduction¶

Prosper is the first peer-to-peer lending market place in America. This document is used to visualize a loan data from Prosper. It contains 113,937 loans with 81 variables on each loan, including loan amount, borrower rate (or interest rate),current loan status, borrower income, and many others.¶

# convert some columns into ordered categorical types
categorical_data = {'LoanStatus': ['Current','Completed','Chargedoff','Defaulted','PastDue (31-60 days)','Past Due (61-90 days)','Past Due (91-120 days)','Past Due (16-30 days)','FinalPaymentInProgress','Past Due (>120 days)','Cancelled', 'PastDue (1-15 days)'],
                    'EmploymentStatus': ['Employed','Full-time','Self-employed','Not available','Other','Part-time','Not employed','Retired'],
                    'IncomeRange': ['$25,000-49,999','$50,000-74,999','$100,000+','$75,000-99,999','$1-24,999','$0', 'Not Employeed', 'Not Displayed'],
                    }

for var in categorical_data:
    ordered_var = pd.api.types.CategoricalDtype(ordered = True,
                                                categories = categorical_data[var])
    prosper_loan[var] = prosper_loan[var].astype(ordered_var)

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The dataset contains 113,937 record of loan with 81 features. Most of the variables have number data type and a few with categorical datatype. For example,

Loan Status : Cancelled,Chargedoff,Completed,Current,Defaulted,FinalPaymentInProgress and PastDue.

Listing Category: Not Available,Debt Consolidation,Home Improvement,Business,Personal Loan,Student Use,Auto, Other,Baby&Adoption,Boat,Cosmetic Procedure,Engagement Ring,Green Loans,Household Expenses,Large Purchases,Medical/Dental,Motorcycle,RV,Taxes,Vacation,Wedding Loans

EmploymentStatus: 'Employed','Full-time','Self-employed','Not available','Other','Part-time','Not employed','Retired'

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I am interested to find out which features highly affect the loan status of a borrower.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I have selected around 11 variables to help me on my investigation.I think the income range, stated monthly income, loan original amount and monthly loan payment highly affect the loan status variable. On top of that borrower APR and borrower rate affects the status, since the higher the loan amount is the higher loan rate and borrower APR will be. The other variables that can affect the status are the term of the loan, the employment status of the borrower, ProsperScore and CreditScoreRangeUpper.

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

During the exploration of Prosper loan dataset, I have found around 12 columns for the analysis part. I have checked the distribution of 8 of the variables by using histplot of matplotlib and countplot of seaborn library.

Among the variables, 5 of them hava categorical datatype. When visualizing the distribution of LoanOriginalAmount, I have transformed the describe() of LoanOriginalAmount variable by using scale of log10.In addition, I have adjusted the binsize using base power and the transformed describe().Similarly, I have adjusted the binsize of StatedMonthlyIncome by using the base power.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

I have used transformation on the distribution of StatedMonthlyIncome and LoanOriginalAmount, because there was a long tail on the distribution of this variables. This happened, because the variables hold large values. I have removed unused categorical types on the variables IncomeRange and LoanStatus, Since the value counts of this types is 0.

I have used heatmap to findout relationships among each variables. The relationships is represented by the coeffcient of correlation. Next I have used the regplot function of seaborn library to visualize the relationship between LoanOriginalAmount and ProsperScore resulting negative relationship. Other functions I have used for bivariate exploration are violinplot and pairGrid functions of the seaborn library. Based the outcome of the pairgrid visualization, I have found out that some of the relationships are negatively correlated and the others have a postive correlation. To mention examples, Borrower rate and BorrowerAPR have a positve correlational relationship and Borrower rate and ProsperScore have negative correlational relationship. Conclusions¶

After performing this analysis, I have concluded that some of the variables are highly correlated to one another.Looking back to the dataset, I have chosen around eleven variables to explore the relationship of loan status between the selected variables. Based on the procedure, I have first explored the distribution of borrowers monthly loan payment based on their employment status and prosper score. In addition, I have checked the relationship among loan status,term, monthly loan payment and prosper score. The visualization shows that borrowers with current loan status and prosper score pay their monthly loan payment within mostly within 60 months and 36 months respectively. Last but not least, I have checked the relationship between the loan status of a borrower with certain employment status and borrowerAPR.
